he autophagic degradation of connexins by inhibiting the PI3K&#x2010;AKT&#x2010;mTOR signaling pathway. Front Biosci Landmark Ed. 2024;29(5):201. https://doi.org/10.31083/j.fbl2905201</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>Torelli S, Agnihotri V, Zhu H, Wang Z, Cheng P, Rhee JW. Clinical relevance and mechanistic underpinnings of tyrosine kinase inhibitor associated cardiotoxicities. Curr Treat Options Cardiovasc Med. 2024;27(1):10. https://doi.org/10.1007/s11936&#x2010;024&#x2010;01067&#x2010;x</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>Niemann CU, Herman SEM, Maric I, Gomez&#x2010;Rodriguez J, Biancotto A, Chang BY, et&#xa0;al. Disruption of in&#xa0;vivo chronic lymphocytic leukemia tumor&#x2010;microenvironment interactions by ibrutinib &#x2013; findings from an investigator initiated phase 2 study. Clin Cancer Res Off J Am Assoc Cancer Res. 2016;22(7):7. https://doi.org/10.1158/1078&#x2010;0432.CCR&#x2010;15&#x2010;1965</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>Lin CH, Elkholy KH, Wani NA, Li D, Hu P, Barajas JM, et&#xa0;al. Ibrutinib potentiates Antihepatocarcinogenic efficacy of sorafenib by targeting EGFR in tumor cells and BTK in immune cells in the stroma. Mol Cancer Ther. 2020;19(2):2&#x2013;396. https://doi.org/10.1158/1535&#x2010;7163.MCT&#x2010;19&#x2010;0135</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>Gordon MJ, Jones JE, George B, Peterson C, Burger JA, Jain N, et&#xa0;al. Long&#x2010;term outcomes in patients with chronic lymphocytic leukemia treated with ibrutinib: focus on hypertension and cardiovascular toxicity. Cancer. 2023;129(14):2192&#x2013;2200. https://doi.org/10.1002/cncr.34787</Citation></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="PubMed-not-MEDLINE" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">42333180</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>23</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>23</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Print">0971-4502</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Print"><Volume>42</Volume><Issue>4</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Jul</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Indian journal of hematology &amp; blood transfusion : an official journal of Indian Society of Hematology and Blood Transfusion</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Indian J Hematol Blood Transfus</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Zanubrutinib, Lenalidomide, and Rituximab Demonstrate Efficacy in Relapsed/Refractory Central Nervous System Lymphoma: A Single - Center Retrospective Study.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1214</StartPage><EndPage>1220</EndPage><MedlinePgn>1214-1220</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1007/s12288-025-02109-5</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">Relapsed/refractory primary central nervous system lymphoma (r/r - PCNSL) is associated with a dismal prognosis. The Zanubrutinib, Lenalidomide, and Rituximab regimen has been shown to be effective and well - tolerated in treating relapsed/refractory PCNSL, particularly among patients with the MYD88 and CD79B Mutations (MCD). Nevertheless, there is a dearth of published data on the "real - world" application of this regimen, especially in patients with central nervous system (CNS) involvement.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS AND MATERIALS" NlmCategory="METHODS">This study included 16 patients diagnosed with relapsed/refractory primary central nervous system lymphoma. These patients had received at least one prior line of treatment and were administered the Zanubrutinib, Lenalidomide, and Rituximab therapy within a compassionate - use program from January 2020 to September 2023.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Upon completion of the induction therapy, 12 (75%) patients achieved complete remission (CR), and 1 (6%) patient achieved partial remission (PR). One patient (6%) had stable disease (SD), while 3 patients (19%) had progressive disease (PD), resulting in an overall response rate (ORR) of 81%. At a median follow - up of 416 days (ranging from 59 to 877 days), most of the responses were maintained. Six (46%) patients had radiologically confirmed PD. The 2 - year progression - free survival (PFS) rate was 48.6%, and the 2 - year overall survival (OS) rate was 72.3%. In the subgroup analysis, participants with the MCD subtype exhibited significantly better PFS (<i>p</i>&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.005).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">The Zanubrutinib, Lenalidomide, and Rituximab regimen appears to have promising efficacy and acceptable safety in treating relapsed/refractory PCNSL, particularly for patients with the MCD subtype.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; Indian Society of Hematology and Blood Transfusion 2025. Springer Nature or its licensor (e.g. a society or other partner) holds exclusive rights to this article under a publishing agreement with the author(s) or other rightsholder(s); author self-archiving of the accepted manuscript version of this article is solely governed by the terms of such publishing agreement and applicable law.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Zhang</LastName><ForeName>Jingcheng</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-7555-8848</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Hematology, Affiliated Jinhua Hospital, Zhejiang University School of Medicine, Jinhua, 321000 China.</Affiliation><Identifier Source="ROR">https://ror.org/00a2xv884</Identifier><Identifier Source="GRID">grid.13402.34</Identifier><Identifier Source="ISNI">0000 0004 1759 700X</Identifier></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>He</LastName><ForeName>Fang</ForeName><Initials>F</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Hematology, Affiliated Jinhua Hospital, Zhejiang University School of Medic